owl:Ontology.rdfs:comment: generated by S.M.Richard for Loop3D project

generic definition of time ordinal eras and older boundaries for eras, based on all eras defined in ISC 2020 time scale. The intention is to define generic time scale concepts to unify the materialization of those concepts in different versions of the time scale. Each specific materialization is linked to the unifying element as 'part of'.
owl:Ontology.rdfs:label: Geologic Timescale Framework

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Most granular geochronologic time interval; one or more Ages are grouped into an Epoch
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Age (time scale rank)

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: How will this be defined? Must contain at least one Era and have duration longer than some Era?
An Epoch may be subdivided into Ages. Epochs are grouped into Periods. Example epochs: Eocene, Pleistocene
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Epoch

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Named rank for geochronologic time interval. An Era may be subdivided into Periods. Eras are grouped into Eons
Named rank for geochronologic time interval. Periods may be subdivided into Epochs. Periods are grouped into an Era.
Named rank for geochronologic time interval. Sub-Periods may be subdivided into Epochs. Sub-Periods are grouped into a period.
hight ranking geochronlogic time interval, parts are eons
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Supereon

owl:NamedIndividual.rdfs:comment: Fortunian is the earliest of the five Siberian Early Cambrian ages, and also the most recently recognized. The stage and its equivalents were only added to the Cambrian in 1992. http://palaeos.com/paleozoic/cambrian/fortunian.html
Interval for grouping all specific instances of the Fortunian Age

The name 'Fortunian Stage' is proposed as the lowest stage of the Cambrian and the lower part of the proposed Terreneuvian Series. The base of the Fortunian Stage corresponds to the defined GSSP for the base of the Cambrian (FAD of Trichophycus pedum and base of the T. pedum Zone [ichnofossils] in the Fortune Head section, Burin Peninsula, Newfoundland, Canada). Its top will be defined by the base of the overlying stage, which is presently undefined. Prepared by E. Landing for ISCS, January 2007; http://www.palaeontology.geo.uu.se/ISCS/ISCS_Terreneuvian_Fortunian_2007.pdf

owl:NamedIndividual.rdfs:comment: Interval for grouping all specific instances of the Thanetian Age

The Thanetian Stage concept was first used by Renevier (1873) who included the Thanet Sands with Cyprina morris and the Woolwich and Reading Beds with Cyrena cuneiformis. Its meaning was subsequently narrowed by Dollfus (1880), who included only the Thanet Sands, the original type-strata on the Isle of Thanet in southeast England. Since 1880 the term Thanetian has consistently been used with the restricted meaning of Dollfus (Bignot et al. 1997). https://doi.org/10.18814/epiiugs/2011/v34i4/002
